With I.T Collect your Confidential Information is SECURE

You no longer have to risk leaving your electronic goods at the local government transfer station or out on the nature strip where the next person that comes along can take them. Additionally, I.T. Collect ensures that your electronic waste items are not bundled up and on-sold to be refurbished and resold either in Australia or overseas. 

I.T. Collect ensures there is a chain of custody of your electronic items from pickup to destruction. 

All e-waste items are disassembled and the various components are sorted into their recycling streams:

Hard drives, solid state drives, memory chips etc are all shredded. There is no risk of your data being accessed by anyone. 

Batteries are removed and recycled to approved environmental standards.

Printer/fax toner/ink cartridges are removed and recycled. 

The remaining plastic, glass and metal components are shredded and sorted into their correct recycling streams.
 
We provide you with a Certificate of Destruction confirming that your items have been destroyed (there is an additional fee if you need an itemised certificate with serial numbers recorded).

Why shouldn't I put rechargeable batteries in the rubbish bin?

Because they can include eco-toxic metals such as cadmium, mercury and lead, which can be harmful to the environment when disposed of to landfill. The metals can leak from the battery and contaminate soil and groundwater.

Cardinia Waste and Recyclers is part of the Future Materials Group. This business has been operating for more than a decade providing Melbourne with a local recycling transfer station in an easily accessible location just off the Princes Freeway in Pakenham.

This is a Paintback site. 
NO charge / DROP OFF only service.
Paintback is a cost-effective solution for households and trade painters to remove unwanted paint and packaging. This program is the first such national program in the world to be developed and voluntary run by the paint industry. More than a million litres of unwanted paint has been diverted from landfill in the first year. 
Contact: 1300 390 380
